________________________________________
1️⃣ Can we Persist Data From Both Sides?
Short Answer
❌ No — the relationship is persisted only by the owning side.
✅ But you can call save() from either entity's repository.
The actual foreign key update happens only from the owning side.
In your example:
•	Department → @OneToMany(mappedBy="department") → Inverse side
•	Employee → @ManyToOne @JoinColumn → Owning side
👉 Employee controls the foreign key (department_id).
________________________________________
2️⃣ What Happens If You Persist From Inverse Side Only?
Example:
Department dept = departmentRepository.findById(1L).get();

Employee emp = new Employee();
emp.setName("Raghav");

dept.getEmployees().add(emp);

departmentRepository.save(dept);
Result
❌ department_id will NOT be set.
Because:
•	Department is inverse side
•	Hibernate ignores relationship changes from inverse side.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Correct Way (Owning Side Must Be Set)
Department dept = departmentRepository.findById(1L).get();

Employee emp = new Employee();
emp.setName("Raghav");

emp.setDepartment(dept); // Owning side

dept.getEmployees().add(emp); // optional but recommended

employeeRepository.save(emp);
Now:
✅ department_id will be stored.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Why JPA Works Like This
Because only one side must control the relationship to avoid conflicts.
So JPA defines:
Side	Role
@ManyToOne	Owning side
@OneToMany(mappedBy)	Inverse side
Only the owning side writes the foreign key.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Fetching Data (Very Different From Persisting)
Fetching is not restricted.
Because both entities have references.
You can fetch:
From Department → Employees
Department dept = departmentRepository.findById(1L).get();
List<Employee> employees = dept.getEmployees();
________________________________________
From Employee → Department
Employee emp = employeeRepository.findById(1L).get();
Department dept = emp.getDepartment();
________________________________________
6️⃣ So Final Answer
Operation	Owning Side	Inverse Side
Persist Relationship	✅ Works	❌ Ignored
Update Relationship	✅ Works	❌ Ignored
Fetch Data	✅ Works	✅ Works
Navigation	Both possible	Both possible
________________________________________
7️⃣ Golden Rule (Interview Answer)
In bidirectional relationships, only the owning side controls the database relationship, while both sides can be used for navigation and fetching.
________________________________________
8️⃣ Best Practice (Helper Method)
To avoid mistakes:
public void addEmployee(Employee emp){
    employees.add(emp);
    emp.setDepartment(this);
}
This keeps both sides synchronized.
