Great observation 👍 Your confusion is very valid, and this is exactly where many developers misunderstand bidirectional mappings. Let's break it clearly.
________________________________________
1️⃣ What I Said Earlier
I said:
Relationship changes must happen from the owning side (Employee).
That statement is correct.
But in your example, the relationship is actually being set on the owning side indirectly.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Look Carefully at Your Code
You used this helper method:
department.addEmployee(employee);
Now look at the implementation:
public void addEmployee(Employee employee) {
    employees.add(employee);
    employee.setDepartment(this);
}
This line is the key:
employee.setDepartment(this);
That means:
✔ The owning side (Employee) is being set.
So even though you call the method from Department, internally it updates the owning side.
________________________________________
3️⃣ What Actually Happens Internally
When this runs:
department.addEmployee(employee);
Two things happen:
1️⃣ Add to collection (inverse side)
Department.employees.add(employee)
2️⃣ Set owning side
Employee.department = department
The second step is what Hibernate cares about.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Why departmentRepository.save() Works
Because of:
cascade = CascadeType.ALL
@OneToMany(mappedBy="department", cascade=CascadeType.ALL)
So when you do:
departmentRepository.save(department);
Hibernate also saves the employees.
But the relationship is still determined by
employee.setDepartment(department)
________________________________________
5️⃣ If Helper Method Did NOT Set Owning Side
If your method was like this:
public void addEmployee(Employee employee) {
    employees.add(employee);
}
Then this code:
department.addEmployee(employee);
departmentRepository.save(department);
Would produce:
employee.department = null
Result:
❌ department_id = NULL
❌ relationship not persisted
________________________________________
6️⃣ So What Actually Matters
Not which repository you call.
What matters is:
owning side must be updated
In this mapping:
Employee.department
________________________________________
7️⃣ Real Rule (Most Accurate Statement)
Action	Required
Save parent	Optional
Save child	Optional
Set owning side	Mandatory
________________________________________
8️⃣ Correct Mental Model
Think like this:
Department → just a view of the relationship
Employee → controls the database FK
So:
Employee.department = department
is what actually writes:
department_id
________________________________________
9️⃣ Interview-Level Explanation
If an interviewer asks:
Why does saving from the parent side work in bidirectional OneToMany?
Correct answer:
Because the helper method sets the owning side (ManyToOne), and cascading persists the child entities. The actual relationship is still controlled by the owning side.
________________________________________
🔟 One More Important Tip
Always use helper methods like this:
public void addEmployee(Employee employee) {
    employees.add(employee);
    employee.setDepartment(this);
}
This ensures both sides stay consistent.
