Great 👍 Now let's understand the very tricky Hibernate behavior you asked about.
Sometimes when using @OneToMany, Hibernate executes SQL like:
INSERT
INSERT
UPDATE
UPDATE
Developers expect only INSERT statements, but Hibernate performs extra UPDATE queries. Let's understand why this happens.
________________________________________
1️⃣ Scenario Example
Entities:
Department
@Entity
public class Department {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    private String name;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "department", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    private List<Employee> employees = new ArrayList<>();

}
________________________________________
Employee
@Entity
public class Employee {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    private String name;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "department_id")
    private Department department;

}
________________________________________
2️⃣ Example Code
Department dept = new Department();
dept.setName("IT");

Employee emp1 = new Employee();
emp1.setName("Raghav");

Employee emp2 = new Employee();
emp2.setName("Arjun");

dept.addEmployee(emp1);
dept.addEmployee(emp2);

departmentRepository.save(dept);
________________________________________
3️⃣ Expected SQL (What Developers Think)
INSERT INTO department
INSERT INTO employee
INSERT INTO employee
________________________________________
4️⃣ Actual SQL Hibernate May Generate
INSERT INTO department (name)

INSERT INTO employee (name, department_id)

INSERT INTO employee (name, department_id)

UPDATE employee SET department_id = ?
UPDATE employee SET department_id = ?
Extra UPDATE queries appear.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Why Hibernate Does This
Because of entity state management inside the Persistence Context.
When you persist Department:
1️⃣ Hibernate inserts the parent first.
INSERT department
2️⃣ Then inserts employees.
But sometimes Hibernate initially inserts employees without the FK, then updates it later once the parent ID is fully known.
Example internal process:
INSERT employee (name, department_id = NULL)
Then:
UPDATE employee SET department_id = 1
________________________________________
6️⃣ When This Happens More Often
Extra updates usually happen when:
•	IDs are generated with IDENTITY
•	Entities are flushed in different phases
•	Relationship is synchronized later in the persistence context
________________________________________
7️⃣ How to Reduce Extra Updates
Best practices:
Always set owning side before saving
employee.setDepartment(department);
Use helper methods
public void addEmployee(Employee employee){
    employees.add(employee);
    employee.setDepartment(this);
}
Use proper cascading
cascade = CascadeType.ALL
________________________________________
8️⃣ Important Internal Concept
Hibernate maintains a Persistence Context (First Level Cache).
Inside it, entities go through states:
State	Meaning
Transient	New object
Managed	Attached to persistence context
Detached	Removed from context
Removed	Scheduled for deletion
When relationships change, Hibernate schedules SQL updates during flush.
________________________________________
9️⃣ Real Reason Developers See Extra Updates
If relationship synchronization happens after insertion, Hibernate must issue an UPDATE to fix the FK.
________________________________________
🔟 Best Production Practice
Always maintain both sides of relationship before persistence:
Department dept = new Department();

Employee emp = new Employee();

dept.getEmployees().add(emp);
emp.setDepartment(dept);
Then persist.
________________________________________
🎯 Senior-Level Interview Answer
If asked:
Why does Hibernate sometimes execute UPDATE after INSERT in OneToMany mappings?
Answer:
Because Hibernate manages entity relationships inside the persistence context.
 If the foreign key value is not fully determined at insert time, Hibernate inserts
 the child entity first and later updates the foreign key once the relationship is synchronized.
